# CSS Rule: Core Style

When writing or modifying CSS, prefer modern, native CSS over preprocessor features and JS-driven workarounds. Most of what people reach for SCSS to do (nesting, custom properties, color functions) is now in baseline CSS.

## Match the project

- Match the project's framework: vanilla CSS, CSS Modules, Tailwind, styled-components, vanilla-extract, Open Props. Do not mix paradigms in the same component.
- If Tailwind is configured: prefer utility classes for layout, spacing, and typography. Reach for custom CSS only for behavioural CSS (animations, container queries, complex selectors) where utilities are awkward.
- Match the BEM (or other) naming convention if the project uses one.

## Selectors

- Prefer single-class selectors. Element selectors only on resets and global typography.
- Specificity wars are won by **using lower specificity**, not by adding more. `!important` is almost always a sign you took a wrong turn three commits ago.
- Avoid IDs as styling hooks. IDs are unique by spec and unbeatable on specificity — they make overrides painful.
- Use `:is()` and `:where()` to keep specificity low:
  ```css
  /* :where(...) contributes 0 specificity */
  .card :where(h1, h2, h3) { margin-block: 0.5em; }
  ```
- Use `:has()` for "container styled by descendant" patterns:
  ```css
  .form-group:has(input:invalid) { border-color: red; }
  ```

## Custom properties

- Use CSS custom properties (`--name`) for design tokens. They cascade, can be overridden per element, and work with `calc()`:
  ```css
  :root {
    --color-bg: #fff;
    --space-xs: 0.25rem;
    --space-sm: 0.5rem;
    --space-md: 1rem;
  }

  .card {
    background: var(--color-bg);
    padding: var(--space-md);
  }
  ```
- Custom properties beat SCSS variables for runtime theming (dark mode, multi-brand) since they're live.
- Use SCSS variables only for **compile-time** values that change a calculated literal (e.g., a breakpoint width used in a `@media` query, which `var()` can't appear inside).

## Logical properties

Use logical properties (`-inline`, `-block`) over physical (`-left`, `-right`, `-top`, `-bottom`) for layout-direction-agnostic CSS — important for RTL support:

```css
/* Good */
.card {
  margin-block: 1rem;       /* top + bottom */
  margin-inline: auto;      /* left + right */
  padding-inline-start: 1rem;
  border-inline-end: 1px solid #ccc;
}

/* Avoid */
.card {
  margin-top: 1rem;
  margin-bottom: 1rem;
  padding-left: 1rem;
  border-right: 1px solid #ccc;
}
```

## Layers (`@layer`)

Cascade layers control specificity-independent override order. Use them for vendor CSS, framework base, components, and utilities:

```css
@layer reset, base, components, utilities;

@layer reset {
  *, *::before, *::after { box-sizing: border-box; }
}

@layer components {
  .button { ... }
}

@layer utilities {
  .text-center { text-align: center; }
}
```

Anything in a later layer beats anything in an earlier layer, regardless of selector specificity.

## Nesting

Native CSS nesting (Chrome 112+, Safari 16.5+, Firefox 117+) replaces most SCSS nesting needs:

```css
.card {
  padding: 1rem;

  & > .title {
    font-size: 1.5rem;
  }

  &:hover {
    background: #f0f0f0;
  }

  @media (min-width: 768px) {
    padding: 2rem;
  }
}
```

- The leading `&` is required in spec-mode (though some compilers allow elision).
- Don't nest more than 2 levels deep. Deep nesting maps to high specificity selectors and unreadable diffs.

## Container queries

Use `@container` over `@media` when the component should respond to its **container** size, not the viewport:

```css
.card {
  container-type: inline-size;
  container-name: card;
}

@container card (min-width: 400px) {
  .card-body {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 2fr;
  }
}
```

Containerized components compose better; the same `.card` reacts to a sidebar (narrow) and a hero (wide) without media-query gymnastics.

## Scoping

- CSS Modules (`*.module.css`) for component-scoped styles when the project uses them.
- `@scope` (newer; check browser support) for limited-scope styles in vanilla CSS:
  ```css
  @scope (.article) to (.aside) {
    p { line-height: 1.6; }
  }
  ```

## Colour

- Use modern `oklch()` for new palettes — it's perceptually uniform; lightness changes look like lightness changes:
  ```css
  --color-primary: oklch(60% 0.18 240);
  --color-primary-hover: oklch(50% 0.18 240);
  ```
- Use `color-mix(in oklch, var(--color-primary) 80%, white)` for derived shades.
- Use `light-dark(var(--bg-light), var(--bg-dark))` for automatic light/dark mode where browser support permits.
- Avoid named colours (`red`, `blue`) except in resets/demos.

## Layout

- Grid for two-dimensional layout (rows AND columns).
- Flexbox for one-dimensional layout.
- `gap` over margin hacks for spacing children.
- `aspect-ratio` over the padding-bottom hack for fixed-ratio boxes.
- `min(...)`, `max(...)`, `clamp(min, ideal, max)` for fluid sizing without media queries:
  ```css
  font-size: clamp(1rem, 0.5rem + 1.5vw, 1.5rem);
  width: min(100% - 2rem, 60rem);
  ```

## Typography

- Set `font-family` on `:root` or `body`; let it cascade.
- Use `system-ui` or a variable font with `font-variation-settings` over multiple webfont files.
- `line-height: 1.5` for body, `line-height: 1.2` for headings.
- `text-wrap: balance` for headlines, `text-wrap: pretty` for paragraphs (where supported).

## Animations

- `@keyframes` for non-trivial animation; transitions for state changes.
- Animate only `transform` and `opacity` on hot paths — they're cheap. Avoid animating `width`, `height`, `top`, `left` (layout-triggering).
- Respect `prefers-reduced-motion`:
  ```css
  @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
    *, *::before, *::after {
      animation-duration: 0.01ms !important;
      transition-duration: 0.01ms !important;
    }
  }
  ```

## Tooling

- `stylelint` for linting.
- `prettier` for formatting.
- PostCSS plugins handle vendor prefixes — don't write them by hand.
- `purgecss` / Tailwind's JIT for tree-shaking.

## Anti-patterns

- `!important` (except in narrowly-scoped utility classes).
- `* { margin: 0; padding: 0 }` heavyweight resets — use a modern reset (Andy Bell's, Josh Comeau's) instead.
- Magic numbers in `px` for spacing — use `rem` or design tokens.
- Hidden-via-`display: none` for "accessibility" — use `aria-hidden` + appropriate visibility helpers.
- Inline styles in production templates (except for JS-driven dynamic values).
- Hover-only interactions without a focus equivalent — kills keyboard navigation.

## Examples

### Good

```css
@layer reset, base, components, utilities;

@layer base {
  :root {
    --color-bg: oklch(98% 0.005 240);
    --color-fg: oklch(20% 0.02 240);
    --space-xs: 0.25rem;
    --space-sm: 0.5rem;
    --space-md: 1rem;
    --space-lg: 1.5rem;
  }

  body {
    background: var(--color-bg);
    color: var(--color-fg);
    font-family: system-ui, sans-serif;
    line-height: 1.5;
  }
}

@layer components {
  .card {
    container-type: inline-size;
    background: var(--color-bg);
    padding: var(--space-md);
    border-radius: 0.5rem;

    & > .card-title {
      font-size: clamp(1.25rem, 1rem + 1vw, 1.75rem);
      margin-block-end: var(--space-sm);
    }

    &:has(img) {
      padding-inline: 0;
    }
  }

  @container (min-width: 30rem) {
    .card { padding: var(--space-lg); }
  }
}
```

### Bad

```css
/* IDs, specificity wars, physical props, no design tokens, !important */
#main-content .card.card-default h1.title {
  margin-top: 16px !important;
  margin-left: 8px !important;
  font-size: 24px;
}

#main-content .card.card-default h1.title:hover {
  color: red;
}
```
